{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499312"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:58:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:58:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1484"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1484"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.14,0.53,0.02,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1484"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83435"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1484"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1484"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68336"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"788"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8780"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9429"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28471"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34976"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83435"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old woman presents to the clinic with a complaint of thick, curved, and discoloured toenails on her right foot. She reports that the nails have been gradually thickening over the past several years and have become increasingly difficult to trim. The nail is yellow and appears to be lifted away from the nail bed (Image). The patient denies any pain or discomfort associated with the nail. She has a history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and hypertension for which she takes metformin and perindopril respectively.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first line treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical terbinafine","Surgical nail avulsion","Regular debridement and trimming","Topical betamethasone","Topical mupirocin"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient in the clinical scenario is presenting with signs and symptoms consistent with onychogryphosis which is a condition where the toenail becomes thickened, curved and discoloured due to repetitive trauma or pressure on the nail plate. The signs and symptoms of onychogryphosis include a thick, discoloured toenail that is difficult to trim or maintain. The risk factors for onychogryphosis include age, diabetes, and poor circulation, which may make it more difficult for the body to repair the nail plate after damage. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular debridement and trimming\u003C/strong\u003E involve regular trimming and debridement of the affected nail to relieve pressure and improve appearance. This may be appropriate for patients with mild to moderate onychogryphosis who are not experiencing significant discomfort or impairment. This option also carries the benefit of being non-invasive and low-risk. It is important that the patient has well-fitting shoes that do not exacerbate the repetitive trauma and pressure on the nail plate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical terbinafine \u003C/strong\u003Emay be appropriate for a patient with onychomycosis, which is a fungal infection of the toenail. Onychomycosis typically presents as thickened, discoloured, and brittle toenails, which can be painful and difficult to manage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical nail avulsion\u003C/strong\u003E involves removing the entire nail plate and may be appropriate if the onychogryphosis is severe and causing significant discomfort or impairment. However, this option carries the risk of infection, and may not be appropriate for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical betamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E would be ineffective for onychogryphosis, as it is typically caused by mechanical pressure or trauma and not an inflammatory condition. Additionally, the use of corticosteroids may increase the risk of fungal or bacterial infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical mupirocin\u003C/strong\u003E would not be an appropriate option for the treatment of onychogryphosis. Onychogryphosis is a condition that causes thickening and curvature of the toenail due to mechanical pressure or trauma, not due to a bacterial infection. Therefore, the use of topical antibiotic cream would not address the underlying cause of the condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Regular debridement and trimming are the treatment of choice for onychogryphosis.","Onychogryphosis is often associated with repetitive trauma or pressure on the nail plate, particularly in older adults."],"references":["Tosun S, Tosun B. Onychogryphosis. J Am Podiatr Med Assoc. 2020 Jul 1;110(4):Article_17. doi: 10.7547/18-155. PMID: 33021642. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33021642/","Ko D, Lipner SR. Onychogryphosis: Case Report and Review of the Literature. Skin Appendage Disord. 2018 Oct;4(4):326-330. doi: 10.1159/000485854. Epub 2018 Jan 10. PMID: 30410908; PMCID: PMC6219229. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30410908/","Frazier WT, Santiago-Delgado ZM, Stupka KC 2nd. Onychomycosis: Rapid Evidence Review. Am Fam Physician. 2021 Oct 1;104(4):359-367. PMID: 34652111. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34652111/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68336"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1484"}}